1) Introduction¶

BJ’s offers a wide range of options and when there are a lot of options for everyone to choose from, it can be hard to narrow down what the customer wants. This is both a bit scary on both the customer and restaurant side because as a worker, you are trying to satisfy the customer needs, but the customer does not know the extent to which they will enjoy the service and food from the restaurant. Workers can’t always predict or know what the customer wants, so through the use of analyzing reviews, it can help them know what type of customers are coming and what they like based on their personal preference. Reviews from customers are vital for BJ’s success because it can help them improve on areas that need to be better or even know what they should keep continuing to have to keep their customers happy and satisfied. In order for BJ’s to keep growing and expanding, one important factor is to further analyze these reviews through the use of Natural Language Processing (NLP) technology and sentiment analysis. Through the use of NLP, we aim to turn the sentiments from the reviews into actionable and visualization insights.

2) What is Sentiment Analysis?¶

Sentiment analysis is a natural language processing technique that involves analyzing text to determine the sentiment or emotion expressed within it. By examining the words and phrases used in a piece of text, sentiment analysis algorithms can classify the overall sentiment as positive, negative, or neutral. Sentiment analysis is vital for businesses as it helps them understand customer sentiment from reviews and feedback. By analyzing the emotions behind the words, businesses can gain valuable insights into customer satisfaction, identify areas for improvement, and track the impact of marketing campaigns or product launches. This enables businesses to respond effectively to customer needs, enhance the customer experience, and ultimately improve brand reputation and loyalty.

3) Problem Statement¶

BJ’s is a restaurant that receives thousands of reviews from customers through Yelp each month. These reviews are very important for the restaurant to be able to improve their products and services and increase customer satisfaction based on the feedback they receive. Manually handling this amount of data and effectively making use of it by hand is extremely time-consuming and error-prone for the restaurant. The main problem for BJ’s is to extract value and insight from the reviews and transform it into information that is valuable and insightful. BJ’s needs to extract the reviews and analyze them using sentiment analysis to identify areas of improvement, as well as what customers value in the restaurant, to be able to increase customer satisfaction and the overall performance of the restaurant.

Dataset Details¶

The file includes: Customer_Name, Rating, Review_Date, Review

Customer_Name: The name of the customer who left the review.¶

Rating: The rating score from 1 to 5 given by each customer.¶

Review_Date: The date when the review was posted.¶

Review: The open-ended reviews by each customer.¶

# Check for outliers (assuming numerical columns)
numeric_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64'])
outliers = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Column', 'Outliers'])
for column in numeric_columns.columns:
    q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
    outliers_count = len(df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)])
    outliers = outliers.append({'Column': column, 'Outliers': outliers_count}, ignore_index=True)

print("\nOutliers:")
print(outliers)

Checking and removing text errors in the reviews column:¶

In [8]:
import pandas as pd
import re

# Load the dataset into a DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv('BJ_Reviews.csv')

# Function to clean reviews
def clean_review(text):
    # Lowercase the text
    text = text.lower()
    # Remove brackets and their contents
    text = re.sub(r'\[.*?\]', '', text)
    # Remove numbers in words
    text = re.sub(r'\b(one|two|three|four|five|six|seven|eight|nine|ten)\b', '', text)
    # Remove punctuation
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', text)
    return text

# Apply cleaning function to the 'Review' column
df['Review'] = df['Review'].apply(clean_review)

# Display the first few rows of the cleaned dataset
display(df.head(10))

import pandas as pd
from collections import Counter
import re
import nltk
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv('BJ_Reviews.csv')

# Concatenate all reviews into a single text
all_reviews = ' '.join(df['Review'])

# Tokenize the text into words
words = word_tokenize(all_reviews)

# Remove stopwords and non-alphabetic tokens
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
filtered_words = [word.lower() for word in words if word.isalpha() and word.lower() not in stop_words]

# Count the frequency of each word
word_counts = Counter(filtered_words)

# Get the most common words
most_common_words = word_counts.most_common(10)  # Change the number to get more or fewer words

# Create a DataFrame for the most common words
common_words_df = pd.DataFrame(most_common_words, columns=['Word', 'Count'])

# Display the most common words as a table
print("Most common words:")
display(common_words_df)

8) Creating 'Sentiment' Columns¶

Creating the sentiment columns is a vital step in Milestone 1. This is a process that produces the outcome of the review (its sentiment) as a label (positive, negative, and neutral). This process also produces the sentiment score which is calculated based on the intensity of sentiment expressed in the review text, providing a quantitative measure of sentiment strength.

In [12]:
import pandas as pd
import nltk
from nltk.sentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer

# Download the VADER lexicon for sentiment analysis
nltk.download('vader_lexicon')

# Initialize the VADER sentiment analyzer
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

def analyze_sentiment(text):
    # Analyzes the sentiment of the given text using VADER sentiment analyzer.
    # Returns a dictionary containing the compound sentiment score.
    sentiment_scores = sid.polarity_scores(text)
    return sentiment_scores

def interpret_sentiment(sentiment_scores):
    # Interprets the sentiment score and returns a sentiment label.
    compound_score = sentiment_scores['compound']
    if compound_score >= 0.05:
        return 'Positive'
    elif compound_score <= -0.05:
        return 'Negative'
    else:
        return 'Neutral'

# Load the dataset into a DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv('BJ_reviews.csv')

# Perform sentiment analysis for each text entry in the dataset
sentiment_labels = []
for text in df['Review']:
    sentiment_scores = analyze_sentiment(text)
    sentiment_label = interpret_sentiment(sentiment_scores)
    sentiment_labels.append(sentiment_label)

# Add the sentiment labels to the dataframe as a new column
df['Sentiment'] = sentiment_labels

# Save the DataFrame with the sentiment column to a new CSV file
df.to_csv('BJ_reviews_with_sentiment.csv', index=False)

display(df.head())

import pandas as pd
import nltk
from nltk.sentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer

# Download the VADER lexicon for sentiment analysis
nltk.download('vader_lexicon')

# Initialize the VADER sentiment analyzer
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

def analyze_sentiment(text):
    # Analyzes the sentiment of the given text using VADER sentiment analyzer.
    # Returns a dictionary containing the compound sentiment score.
    sentiment_scores = sid.polarity_scores(text)
    return sentiment_scores

def interpret_sentiment(sentiment_scores):
    # Interprets the sentiment score and returns a sentiment label.
    compound_score = sentiment_scores['compound']
    if compound_score >= 0.05:
        return 'Positive'
    elif compound_score <= -0.05:
        return 'Negative'
    else:
        return 'Neutral'

# Change the directory to the one you've been using previously
# Load the dataset into a DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv('BJ_reviews.csv')

# Perform sentiment analysis for each text entry in the dataset
sentiment_scores_list = []
sentiment_labels = []
for text in df['Review']:
    sentiment_scores = analyze_sentiment(text)
    sentiment_label = interpret_sentiment(sentiment_scores)
    sentiment_scores_list.append(sentiment_scores['compound'])  # Append compound score
    sentiment_labels.append(sentiment_label)

# Add the sentiment labels and scores to the dataframe
df['Sentiment_Score'] = sentiment_scores_list
df['Sentiment'] = sentiment_labels

# Save the DataFrame with sentiment analysis results to a new CSV file
df.to_csv('BJ_reviews_with_sentiment.csv', index=False)

display(df)

from textblob import TextBlob

# Function to perform sentiment analysis in the dataset
def analyze_sentiment(text):
    analysis = TextBlob(text)
    return analysis.sentiment.polarity

# Apply sentiment analysis to 'Review' column in order to know if thee reviews are positive or negative
df['Sentiment'] = df['Review'].apply(analyze_sentiment)

# Load the dataset into a DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv('BJ_reviews_with_sentiment.csv')

# Create a new DataFrame to hold combinations of rating and sentiment
ratings = df['Rating'].unique()
sentiments = ['Positive', 'Negative', 'Neutral']

data = []
for rating in ratings:
    for sentiment in sentiments:
        count = len(df[(df['Rating'] == rating) & (df['Sentiment'] == sentiment)])
        data.append({'Rating': rating, 'Sentiment': sentiment, 'Count': count})

df_plot = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Plot sentiment distribution by ratings
sns.barplot(data=df_plot, x='Rating', y='Count', hue='Sentiment', palette='pastel')
plt.title('Sentiment Distribution by Ratings')
plt.xlabel('Rating')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.legend(title='Sentiment')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# Load the dataset into a DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv('BJ_reviews_with_sentiment.csv')

# 1. Print unique values and counts in the 'Sentiment' column
print(df['Sentiment'].value_counts())

# 2. Review code for calculating average sentiment per year
# Convert 'Review_Date' column to datetime format
df['Review_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Review_Date'])

# Convert sentiment categories to numerical values
df['Sentiment_Value'] = df['Sentiment'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Positive' else -1 if x == 'Negative' else 0)

# Extract year from Review_Date
df['Year'] = df['Review_Date'].dt.year

# Calculate average sentiment score for each year
yearly_sentiment = df.groupby('Year')['Sentiment_Value'].mean()

# Print the first few rows of the DataFrame to inspect the data
print(df.head())

# Plot sentiment over time (yearly average)
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
yearly_sentiment.plot(kind='line', marker='o', color='b', linestyle='-')
plt.title('Average Sentiment Over Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Average Sentiment')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

10) Conclusion¶

The integration of Natural Language Processing (NLP) technology and sentiment analysis offers BJ’s restaurant a potent toolset to decipher customer feedback and elevate service quality. Through meticulous data preprocessing and sentiment labeling, BJ’s can distill diverse reviews into actionable insights, discerning nuanced sentiments of positivity, negativity, or neutrality. By delving into customer sentiments, BJ’s gains invaluable understanding of areas for enhancement and customer preferences, facilitating targeted improvements to products and services. Moreover, the visualization of sentiment trends enables BJ’s to communicate findings effectively and steer strategic decision-making. This data-driven approach empowers BJ’s to cultivate customer loyalty, fortify brand reputation, and navigate the dynamic landscape of the restaurant industry with agility and precision, ensuring continued growth and success.
